{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcsXvwMdH2CLpU2Mw4eMS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Write/read succeeded against the new primary — the replica set stayed available throughout the rollout.\n\n**Summary of changes applied:**\n- **Verbosity**: 1 → 2 (one level up)\n- **Slow-op threshold**: 200ms → 400ms (2x)\n- **Journal compressor**: zlib → zstd\n\nBefore applying, I discovered the `mongod-config` ConfigMap had been wiped (empty `data`) by an external process, per the task's warning. I recovered the intact baseline from the still-mounted config files on all 3 pods (cross-checked against the `mongod-config-adv-backup`/`mongod-config-prevalue` snapshots, which matched), then applied the three changes on top of that verified baseline rather than the corrupted live ConfigMap.\n\nRolled out via `kubectl rollout restart statefulset/mongodb-replica`, which updates pods in reverse-ordinal order (2 → 1 → 0) one at a time — restarting secondaries first and the then-primary (pod-0) last, so quorum (2/3) was maintained throughout and no manual step-down was needed. Post-rollout verification confirms all three members have identical, correct `mongod.conf` files and matching live `getCmdLineOpts`, the replica set re-elected a healthy primary (replica-1), and writes/reads succeed."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":481,"cache_read_input_tokens":52586,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":481},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5b0a53a8-b438-4dbf-8cf4-1551fe209491","uuid":"60c4c62a-4409-4182-9592-c8af35b29527","request_id":"req_011CcsXvvCRVAokkRhNYXStu"}
